The specific online Master of Arts program at the New York Film Academy that culminates in a capstone E-Portfolio is the Master of Arts (MA) in Producing (Online), a three-semester program focused on film and television production skills, where students compile professional-grade materials to showcase their abilities [1].

The eight specific real-world projects that students must compile for this E-Portfolio are: 
1. Short Film Finance Plan (detailed budgeting and funding strategy for a short project); 
2. Feature Film Business Plan (comprehensive finance, marketing, and distribution outline for a full-length film); 
3. TV Series Bible (in-depth guide including character development, episode breakdowns, and production logistics); 
4. Documentary Pitch Deck (research-based presentation with visual concepts and pitching materials for non-fiction); 
5. Web Series Proposal (digital content plan covering audience targeting, scripting, and monetization); 
6. Commercial Production Plan (budget and creative strategy for a speculative advertisement); 
7. Music Video Treatment (conceptual outline with visual style, storyline, and production notes); 
8. Producing Portfolio Compilation (curated assembly of all projects with reflective analyses on industry applications and career readiness) [1][2].

For the Mise-en-scene Exercise assigned to producing students at the New York Film Academy's Los Angeles campus, this hands-on assignment involves students directing a short scene to practice visual storytelling and production management. It is filmed on location at the NYFA Los Angeles campus facilities, including soundstages and outdoor sets provided through partnerships like Warner Bros. Studios. The crew size is limited to 4-6 members, typically including a director (the student), cinematographer, sound technician, and minimal support roles to emphasize efficient collaboration. The directorial structure requires each student to individually direct their own mise-en-scene short, rotating roles in group settings to gain experience in leadership, blocking, and mise-en-scene elements like lighting and composition, without external actors or elaborate props [3][4].

